<section class="faq-section">
	<h2>Frequently Asked Questions About PDF Merging</h2>
	
	<div class="faq-item">
		<h3>Is it safe to merge PDFs using this online tool?</h3>
		<p>Absolutely! This PDF merger is completely client-side - all processing happens locally in your web browser using JavaScript libraries. Your PDF files are never uploaded to our servers, never transmitted over the internet, and we never see or store your documents. It's 100% private and secure.</p>
	</div>
	
	<div class="faq-item">
		<h3>How many PDF files can I merge at once?</h3>
		<p>There's no hard limit on the number of PDFs you can merge. However, very large files or many files may require more processing time and memory. Most users can easily combine 10-20 PDFs without any issues. For the best performance, we recommend merging PDFs in batches if you have dozens of files.</p>
	</div>
	
	<div class="faq-item">
		<h3>Will merging PDFs reduce quality or file size?</h3>
		<p>No quality loss occurs when merging PDFs. The merged output maintains the exact quality of the original files. The final file size will be approximately the sum of all individual PDF file sizes (or slightly larger due to PDF structure overhead).</p>
	</div>
	
	<div class="faq-item">
		<h3>Can I rearrange the order of PDFs before merging?</h3>
		<p>Yes! Use the up and down arrow buttons next to each file to reorder them. Arrange your PDFs in exactly the order you want them to appear in the final merged document.</p>
	</div>
	
	<div class="faq-item">
		<h3>What if my merged PDF is too large?</h3>
		<p>If your merged PDF exceeds size limits for email or upload, you have several options: compress the original PDFs before merging, merge files in smaller batches, or use our <a href="../pdf-split/">PDF Split Tool</a> to break the merged file into smaller sections.</p>
	</div>
	
	<div class="faq-item">
		<h3>Can I merge password-protected PDFs?</h3>
		<p>Currently, this tool works best with unprotected PDFs. If you have password-protected PDFs, you'll need to remove the password protection before merging them.</p>
	</div>
